# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: echo-web-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The **client–server model** is a form of messaging pattern in a distributed application structure that partitions tasks or workloads between the providers of a resource or service, called servers, and service requesters, called clients.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Often clients and servers communicate over a computer network on separate hardware, but both client and server may be on the same device.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A server host runs one or more server programs, which share their resources with clients.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A client usually does not share its computing resources, but it requests content or service from a server and may share its own content as part of the request.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Clients, therefore, initiate communication sessions with servers, which await incoming requests.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Examples of computer applications that use the client–server model are email, network printing, and the World Wide Web.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The server component provides a function or service to one or many clients, which initiate requests for such services.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Servers are classified by the services they provide.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] For example, a web server serves web pages and a file server serves computer files.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A shared resource may be any of the server computer's software and electronic components, from programs and data to processors and storage devices.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The sharing of resources of a server constitutes a *service*.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Whether a computer is a client, a server, or both, is determined by the nature of the application that requires the service functions.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] For example, a single computer can run a web server and file server software at the same time to serve different data to clients making different kinds of requests.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The client software can also communicate with server software within the same computer.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Communication between servers, such as to synchronize data, is sometimes called *inter-server* or *server-to-server* communication.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Generally, a service is an abstraction of computer resources and a client does not have to be concerned with how the server performs while fulfilling the request and delivering the response.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The client only has to understand the response based on the relevant application protocol, i.e. the content and the formatting of the data for the requested service.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Clients and servers exchange messages in a request–response messaging pattern.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The client sends a request, and the server returns a response.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This exchange of messages is an example of inter-process communication.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] To communicate, the computers must have a common language, and they must follow rules so that both the client and the server know what to expect.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The language and rules of communication are defined in a communications protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] All protocols operate in the application layer.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The application layer protocol defines the basic patterns of the dialogue.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] To formalize the data exchange even further, the server may implement an application programming interface (API).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The API is an abstraction layer for accessing a service.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] By restricting communication to a specific content format, it facilitates parsing.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] By abstracting access, it facilitates cross-platform data exchange.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A server may receive requests from many distinct clients in a short period.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A computer can only perform a limited number of tasks at any moment, and relies on a scheduling system to prioritize incoming requests from clients to accommodate them.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] To prevent abuse and maximize availability, the server software may limit the availability to clients.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Denial of service attacks are designed to exploit a server's obligation to process requests by overloading it with excessive request rates.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Encryption should be applied if sensitive information is to be communicated between the client and the server.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] When a bank customer accesses online banking services with a web browser (the client), the client initiates a request to the bank's web server.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The customer's login credentials are compared against a database, and the webserver accesses that database server as a client.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] An application server interprets the returned data by applying the bank's business logic and provides the output to the webserver.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Finally, the webserver returns the result to the client web browser for display.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In each step of this sequence of client–server message exchanges, a computer processes a request and returns data.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This is the request-response messaging pattern.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] When all the requests are met, the sequence is complete.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This example illustrates a design pattern applicable to the client–server model: separation of concerns.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Server-side refers to programs and operations that run on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This is in contrast to client-side programs and operations which run on the client.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] "Server-side software" refers to a computer application, such as a web server, that runs on remote server hardware, reachable from a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Operations may be performed server-side because they require access to information or functionality that is not available on the client, or because performing such operations on the client side would be slow, unreliable, or insecure.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Client and server programs may be commonly available ones such as free or commercial web servers and web browsers, communicating with each other using standardized protocols.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Or, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Server-side operations include both those that are carried out in response to client requests, and non-client-oriented operations such as maintenance tasks.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In a computer security context, server-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on a server computer system, rather than on the client side, or in between the two.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] For example, an attacker might exploit an SQL injection vulnerability in a web application in order to maliciously change or gain unauthorized access to data in the server's database.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might break into a server system using vulnerabilities in the underlying operating system and then be able to access database and other files in the same manner as authorized administrators of the server.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In the case of an Internet-dependent user application like Google Earth, while querying and display of map data takes place on the client side, the server is responsible for permanent storage of map data, resolving user queries into map data to be returned to the client, etc.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Web applications and services can be implemented in almost any language, as long as they can return data to standards-based web browsers (possibly via intermediary programs) in formats which they can use.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Client-side refers to operations that are performed by the client in a computer network.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Typically, a client is a computer application, such as a web browser, that runs on a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device, and connects to a server as necessary.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Additionally, if operations can be performed by the client, without sending data over the network, they may take less time, use less bandwidth, and incur a lesser security risk.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example according to standard protocols such as HTTP or FTP, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (e.g. most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both HTTP and FTP).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be termed client-side operations.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In a computer security context, client-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on the client / user's computer system, rather than on the server side, or in between the two.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] As an example, if a server contained an encrypted file or message which could only be decrypted using a key housed on the user's computer system, a client-side attack would normally be an attacker's only opportunity to gain access to the decrypted contents.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] For instance, the attacker might cause malware to be installed on the client system, allowing the attacker to view the user's screen, record the user's keystrokes, and steal copies of the user's encryption keys, etc.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might employ cross-site scripting vulnerabilities to execute malicious code on the client's system without needing to install any permanently resident malware.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Distributed computing projects such as SETI@home and the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search, as well as Internet-dependent applications like Google Earth, rely primarily on client-side operations.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] They initiate a connection with the server (either in response to a user query, as with Google Earth, or in an automated fashion, as with SETI@home), and request some data.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The server selects a data set (a server-side operation) and sends it back to the client.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The client then analyzes the data (a client-side operation), and, when the analysis is complete, displays it to the user (as with Google Earth) and/or transmits the results of calculations back to the server (as with SETI@home).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] An early form of client–server architecture is remote job entry, dating at least to OS/360 (announced 1964), where the request was to run a job, and the response was the output.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] While formulating the client–server model in the 1960s and 1970s, computer scientists building ARPANET (at the Stanford Research Institute) used the terms *server-host* (or *serving host*) and *user-host* (or *using-host*), and these appear in the early documents RFC 5 and RFC 4.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This usage was continued at Xerox PARC in the mid-1970s.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] One context in which researchers used these terms was in the design of a computer network programming language called Decode-Encode Language (DEL).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The purpose of this language was to accept commands from one computer (the user-host), which would return status reports to the user as it encoded the commands in network packets.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Another DEL-capable computer, the server-host, received the packets, decoded them, and returned formatted data to the user-host.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A DEL program on the user-host received the results to present to the user.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Development of DEL was just beginning in 1969, the year that the United States Department of Defense established ARPANET (predecessor of Internet).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] An early use of the word *client* occurs in "Separating Data from Function in a Distributed File System", a 1978 paper by Xerox PARC computer scientists Howard Sturgis, James Mitchell, and Jay Israel.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The authors are careful to define the term for readers, and explain that they use it to distinguish between the user and the user's network node (the client).
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] By 1992, the word *server* had entered into general parlance.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The client-server model does not dictate that server-hosts must have more resources than client-hosts.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Rather, it enables any general-purpose computer to extend its capabilities by using the shared resources of other hosts.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Centralized computing, however, specifically allocates a large number of resources to a small number of computers.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The more computation is offloaded from client-hosts to the central computers, the simpler the client-hosts can be.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] It relies heavily on network resources (servers and infrastructure) for computation and storage.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] A diskless node loads even its operating system from the network, and a computer terminal has no operating system at all; it is only an input/output interface to the server.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In contrast, a rich client, such as a personal computer, has many resources and does not rely on a server for essential functions.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] As microcomputers decreased in price and increased in power from the 1980s to the late 1990s, many organizations transitioned computation from centralized servers, such as mainframes and minicomputers, to rich clients.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This afforded greater, more individualized dominion over computer resources, but complicated information technology management.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] During the 2000s, web applications matured enough to rival application software developed for a specific microarchitecture.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] This maturation, more affordable mass storage, and the advent of service-oriented architecture were among the factors that gave rise to the cloud computing trend of the 2010s.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In addition to the client-server model, distributed computing applications often use the peer-to-peer (P2P) application architecture.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In the client-server model, the server is often designed to operate as a centralized system that serves many clients.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] The computing power, memory and storage requirements of a server must be scaled appropriately to the expected workload.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Load-balancing and failover systems are often employed to scale the server beyond a single physical machine.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Load balancing is defined as the methodical and efficient distribution of network or application traffic across multiple servers in a server farm.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Each load balancer sits between client devices and backend servers, receiving and then distributing incoming requests to any available server capable of fulfilling them.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In a peer-to-peer network, two or more computers (*peers*) pool their resources and communicate in a decentralized system.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Peers are coequal, or equipotent nodes in a non-hierarchical network.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Unlike clients in a client-server or client-queue-client network, peers communicate with each other directly.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] In peer-to-peer networking, an algorithm in the peer-to-peer communications protocol balances load, and even peers with modest resources can help to share the load.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] If a node becomes unavailable, its shared resources remain available as long as other peers offer it.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Ideally, a peer does not need to achieve high availability because other, redundant peers make up for any resource downtime; as the availability and load capacity of peers change, the protocol reroutes requests.
[src:echo-web-go/client-server-model] Both client-server and master-slave are regarded as sub-categories of distributed peer-to-peer systems.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
