[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:echo-web-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:echo-web-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:echo-web-go/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A **router** is a computer and networking device that forwards data packets between computer networks, including internetworks such as the global Internet.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers perform the *traffic directing* functions on the Internet.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router is connected to two or more data lines from different IP networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] When a data packet comes in on a line, the router reads the network address information in the packet header to determine the ultimate destination.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Then, using information in its routing table or routing policy, it directs the packet to the next network on its journey.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A data packet is forwarded from one router to another through an internetwork until it reaches its destination node.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The most familiar type of IP routers are home and small office routers that forward IP packets between the home computers and the Internet.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] More sophisticated routers, such as enterprise routers, connect large business or ISP networks to powerful core routers that forward data at high speed along the optical fiber lines of the Internet backbone.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers can be built from standard computer parts but are mostly specialized purpose-built computers.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Early routers used software-based forwarding, running on a CPU.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] More sophisticated devices use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) to increase performance or add advanced filtering and firewall functionality.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The concepts of a *switching node* using software and an *interface computer* were first proposed by Donald Davies in 1966 for the NPL network.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The same idea was conceived by Wesley Clark the following year for use in the ARPANET, which were named *Interface Message Processors* (IMPs).
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] These computers had fundamentally the same functionality as a router does today.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The idea for a router (called a *gateway* at the time) initially came about through an international group of computer networking researchers called the International Network Working Group (INWG).
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] These gateway devices were different from most previous packet switching schemes in two ways.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] First, they connected dissimilar kinds of networks, such as serial lines and local area networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Second, they were connectionless devices, which had no role in assuring that traffic was delivered reliably, leaving that function entirely to the hosts.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] This particular idea, the end-to-end principle, was contained in the work of Donald Davies.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The concept was explored in practice by various groups, with the intention to produce a working system for internetworking.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] There were three notable contemporaneous programs.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The first was an implementation directed by Louis Pouzin of the CYCLADES network, which was designed and developed during 1972-3.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The second was a program at Xerox PARC to explore new networking technologies, which produced the PARC Universal Packet system.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Some time after early 1974, the first Xerox routers became operational.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Due to corporate intellectual property concerns, it received little attention outside Xerox for years.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The third was a DARPA-initiated program, which began during 1973-4.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] This drew on the work of the other two programs, expanded significantly, and went on to create the TCP/IP architecture in use today.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] University College London (UCL) provided a gateway between British research groups and the ARPANET from 1973 until the late 1980s, latterly using SATNET.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The first true IP router was developed by Ginny Travers at BBN, as part of that DARPA-initiated effort, during 1975–1976.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] By the end of 1976, three PDP-11-based routers were in service in the experimental prototype Internet.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Mike Brecia, Ginny Travers, and Bob Hinden received the IEEE Internet Award for early IP routers in 2008.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The first multiprotocol routers were independently created by staff researchers at MIT and Stanford in 1981 and both were also based on PDP-11s.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Stanford's router program was led by William Yeager and MIT's by Noel Chiappa.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Virtually all networking now uses TCP/IP, but multiprotocol routers are still manufactured.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] They were important in the early stages of the growth of computer networking when protocols other than TCP/IP were in use.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Modern routers that handle both IPv4 and IPv6 are multiprotocol but are simpler devices than those that process AppleTalk, DECnet, IPX, and Xerox protocols.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] From the mid-1970s and in the 1980s, general-purpose minicomputers served as routers.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Modern high-speed routers are network processors or highly specialized computers with extra hardware acceleration added to speed both common routing functions, such as packet forwarding, and specialized functions such as IPsec encryption.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] There is substantial use of Linux and Unix software-based machines, running open source routing code, for research and other applications.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The Cisco IOS operating system was independently designed.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Major router operating systems, such as Junos and NX-OS, are extensively modified versions of Unix software.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] When multiple routers are used in interconnected networks, the routers can exchange information about destination addresses using a routing protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Each router builds up a routing table, a list of routes, between two computer systems on the interconnected networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router may have interfaces for multiple types of physical layer connections, such as copper cables, fiber optic, or wireless transmission.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] It can also support multiple network layer transmission standards.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Each network interface is used to enable data packets to be forwarded from one transmission system to another.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers may also be used to connect two or more logical groups of computer devices known as subnets, each with a unique network prefix.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers may provide connectivity within enterprises, between enterprises and the Internet, or between internet service providers' (ISPs') networks; they are also responsible for directing data between different networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The largest routers (such as the Cisco CRS-1 or Juniper PTX) interconnect the various ISPs, or may be used in large enterprise networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Smaller routers usually provide connectivity for typical home and office networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] All sizes of routers may be found inside enterprises.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The most powerful routers are usually found in ISPs, academic and research facilities.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Large businesses may also need more powerful routers to cope with ever-increasing demands of intranet data traffic.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A hierarchical internetworking model for interconnecting routers in large networks is in common use.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Some routers can connect to Data service units for T1 connections via serial ports.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The hierarchical internetworking model divides enterprise networks into three layers: core, distribution, and access.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Access routers, including small office/home office (SOHO) models, are located at home and customer sites such as branch offices that do not need hierarchical routing of their own.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Typically, they are optimized for low cost.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Some SOHO routers are capable of running alternative free Linux-based firmware like Tomato, OpenWrt, or DD-WRT.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Distribution routers aggregate traffic from multiple access routers.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Distribution routers are often responsible for enforcing quality of service across a wide area network (WAN), so they may have considerable memory installed, multiple WAN interface connections, and substantial onboard data processing routines.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] They may also provide connectivity to groups of file servers or other external networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] In enterprises, a core router may provide a collapsed backbone interconnecting the distribution tier routers from multiple buildings of a campus, or large enterprise locations.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] They tend to be optimized for high bandwidth but lack some of the features of edge routers.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] External networks must be carefully considered as part of the overall security strategy of the local network.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router may include a firewall, VPN handling, and other security functions, or they may be handled by separate devices.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers also commonly perform network address translation, which restricts connections initiated from external connections but is not recognized as a security feature by all experts.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Some experts argue that open source routers are more secure and reliable than closed source routers because errors and potentially exploitable vulnerabilities are more likely to be discovered and addressed in an open-source environment.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers are also often distinguished on the basis of the network in which they operate.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router in a local area network (LAN) of a single organization is called an *interior router*.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router that is operated in the Internet backbone is described as *exterior router*.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] While a router that connects a LAN with the Internet or a wide area network (WAN) is called a *border router*, or *gateway router*.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Routers intended for ISP and major enterprise connectivity usually exchange routing information using the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Wi-Fi routers combine the functions of a router, switch and a wireless access point.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] They are typically devices with a small form factor, operating on the standard electric power supply for residential use.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Connected to the Internet as offered by an Internet service provider, they provide Internet access through Ethernet and Wi-Fi for home or office use.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The main purpose of a router is to connect multiple networks and forward packets destined either for directly attached networks or more remote networks.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router is considered a layer-3 device because its primary forwarding decision is based on the information in the layer-3 IP packet, specifically the destination IP address.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] When a router receives a packet, it searches its routing table to find the best match between the destination IP address of the packet and one of the addresses in the routing table.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Once a match is found, the packet is encapsulated in the layer-2 data link frame for the outgoing interface indicated in the table entry.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A router typically does not look into the packet payload, but only at the layer-3 addresses to make a forwarding decision, plus optionally other information in the header for hints on, for example, quality of service (QoS).
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] For pure IP forwarding, a router is designed to minimize the state information associated with individual packets.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Once a packet is forwarded, the router does not retain any historical information about the packet.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The routing table itself can contain information derived from a variety of sources, such as a default or static routes that are configured manually, or dynamic entries from routing protocols where the router learns routes from other routers.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] A default route is one that is used to route all traffic whose destination does not otherwise appear in the routing table; it is common – even necessary – in small networks, such as a home or small business, where the default route simply sends all non-local traffic to the Internet service provider.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] The default route can be manually configured (as a static route); learned by dynamic routing protocols; or be obtained by DHCP.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Besides deciding to which interface a packet is forwarded, which is handled primarily via the routing table, a router also has to manage congestion when packets arrive at a rate higher than the router can process.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Three policies commonly used are tail drop, random early detection (RED), and weighted random early detection (WRED).
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Tail drop is the simplest and most easily implemented: the router simply drops new incoming packets once buffer space in the router is exhausted.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] RED probabilistically drops datagrams early when the queue exceeds a pre-configured portion of the buffer, until reaching a pre-determined maximum, when it drops all incoming packets, thus reverting to tail drop.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] WRED can be configured to drop packets more readily depending on the type of traffic.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Another function a router performs is traffic classification and deciding which packet should be processed first.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] This is managed through QoS, which is critical when Voice over IP is deployed, so as not to introduce excessive latency.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Yet another function a router performs is called policy-based routing, where special rules are constructed to override the rules derived from the routing table when a packet forwarding decision is made.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Some of the functions may be performed through an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) to avoid the overhead of scheduling CPU time to process the packets.
[src:echo-web-go/router-computing] Others may have to be performed through the CPU as these packets need special attention that cannot be handled by an ASIC.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:echo-web-go/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
